💬 Professor’s Closing Thought

"In Africa, we have always been problem-solvers. Our grandparents navigated deserts by stars. Our mothers stretch one chicken to feed ten guests. Our street vendors calculate change faster than calculators.

Software engineering doesn’t give us problem-solving—it amplifies what we already carry in our blood.

Today, you didn’t learn to code. You remembered how to think.
And that… is where magic begins."

📌 Summary

A problem is simply the gap between where you are and where you want to be—a farmer lacking market prices, a student waiting hours for water. Computational thinking gives you four superpowers to close that gap: decomposition (breaking big problems into small pieces, like preparing egusi soup step by step), pattern recognition (spotting rhythms—mobile money succeeded across Africa through trust + accessibility + speed), abstraction (focusing on what matters—like a griot telling history's essence, not every detail), and algorithms (foolproof recipes—your grandmother's fufu instructions: "Pound 10 minutes. Not 9. Not 11."). You already solve problems daily—finding troTro routes, helping relatives send money. Software engineering simply amplifies this wisdom. Great engineers don't wait for problems—they walk into the world with curious eyes. Remember: In Africa, we've always been problem-solvers. Our grandparents navigated deserts by stars. Software doesn't give us this skill—it amplifies what we already carry in our blood.

 

